{"title":"Entity Tracking in Language Models","domain":"LLM_NLP","seeds":[{"problem":"Prior work claimed language models encode entity states, but evaluations may be confounded by trivial cases that don’t require tracking changes over discourse.","method":"Reanalyze Li et al. (2021) and show that 62.7% of probed states equal the initial state and 32.4% are empty finals, leaving only 12.4% truly non-trivial; the probing classifier achieves 86.8% on trivial but only 3.1% on non-trivial cases, undermining earlier conclusions about genuine entity tracking. This establishes the need for a more controlled test of discourse-driven state tracking."},{"problem":"Evaluate entity tracking in a way that is robust to lexical shortcuts, distributional priors, and slot-filling, and that requires temporal composition of operations.","method":"Introduce a programmatically generated benchmark in a boxes-and-objects world: initial states followed by 0–12 operations (move/put/remove), with cloze-style queries asking for a box’s contents after each step. The dataset is built to satisfy four desiderata (avoid pretraining priors, forbid single-word giveaways, enforce low lexical overlap via AltForms, and prevent slot-filling via initial-state ‘signatures’). Context-dependent variants (Move contents of Box N to M; ambiguous referring expressions with optional adjectives) further require using discourse context to resolve underspecification."},{"problem":"Determine whether pretrained LLMs actually track entities, what training factors make this ability surface, and whether smaller text-only models can learn it.","method":"Using 2-shot prompts, compare GPT-3, GPT-3.5, and Flan-T5: only GPT-3.5 text-davinci-003 exhibits non-trivial entity tracking and remains above a strong random baseline even after many operations; performance persists under low lexical overlap (AltForms) and degrades with increased context dependence (AmbiRef/MoveContents). Ablations across GPT-3 vs. GPT-3.5 indicate models pretrained on code systematically outperform text-only counterparts, including code-davinci-002 without RLHF, implicating code pretraining as key. Finetuning T5-base on the new datasets yields near-perfect accuracy on the base split, generalizes to longer sequences and novel vocab with some degradation, and stays above random under AltForms when trained on longer sequences; context-dependent operations remain challenging."}]}
